\begin_layout Standard
Nano-patterning on surfaces can be achieved by self-organization or artificially
 by direct atom manipulation.
 Surface defects plays a very important role in the formation of patterns
 at nano-scale.
 It has been observed in experiments that preferential nucleation of self-organi
zed nano-structures takes place on surfaces along step edges, dislocations
 and domain boundaries.
 In the deposition of Ge atoms on Si(111)-(7x7) surface, we have found interesti
ng patterns induced by domain boundaries and step edges.
 To understand the formation of these defects induced nano-patterns we have
 proposed a coupled reaction-diffusion equation in the presence of surface
 defects.
 I will discuss a linear model which qualitatively explains the experimentally
 observed pattern.
 Then I will discuss non-linear model which incorporates the effect of exclusion
 on these reaction diffusion processes.
 The effect of exclusion on simple trapping problem has been found to affect
 the stretched exponential behaviour of the asymptotic survival probability.
 This has been recently verified by our numerical simulation.
