\begin_layout Standard
The surface of living cells reads and processes information from the `outside'
 and transmits it to the `inside'.
 It does this by regulating the dynamics and organization of a variety of
 signalling molecules.
 We have shown how the dynamics and organization of many cell surface molecules
 can only be understood by its intimate coupling to an active cytoskeletal
 layer juxtaposed to it.
 We argue that the physical principles underlying the Active Composite cell
 surface provide the natural language for discussing the mechanics of computatio
n and information processing at the cell surface.
 In connecting active mechanics in cells with information processing and
 computation, we bring together two seminal works of A.
 Turing.
\end_layout

